anted to become a full-stack engineer.
He also became a full-stack entrepreneur.=C2=A0
Before Astro Mechanica, Ian ran a successful bootstrapped motorcycle compan=
y. He made things, handled sales, took customer support calls, and did the =
books. He designed the thing, machined the thing, and sold the thing. There=
 aren=E2=80=99t many people who do all three.=C2=A0
Proof came randomly when I was talking to Matt Parlmer [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/b4390c5e-ae2b-4737-a766-ed427c4f74b5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the founder of Not Boring Capit=
al portfolio company General Fabrication [ https://substack.com/redirect/44=
c2f752-f59b-4378-bbff-fbe152842cac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a couple weeks ago. General Fabrication makes=
 machines that can make anything, starting with 3D printers that make plast=
ic parts. As we were talking through potential customers, about companies f=
ull of strong engineers that Matt expects to land, I brought up Astro Mecha=
nica.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThat one=E2=80=99s unlikely,=E2=80=9D Matt told me. =E2=80=9CIan b=
uilt motorcycles by hand. That dude can machine anything himself.=E2=80=9D =
That=E2=80=99s absurdly high praise coming from Matt.=C2=A0
Anyway, while Ian was making motorcycles, his mind was always on the skies.=
 Back in 2019, he started to think through how you=E2=80=99d design an engi=
ne that would make flying private as cheap as airliners.=C2=A0
He knew it was possible. Private jets take 20-30,000 man hours to assemble,=
 which is crazy, because a car, which is more mechanically complicated, tak=
es 40-50.=C2=A0
(I like this way of thinking. Valar Atomics CEO Isaiah Taylor made a simila=
r point about nuclear reactor construction on Age of Miracles [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/fdd4d8e8-f1bc-4772-b3f5-ab33d193656c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Elon Musk has a related =
concept: the Idiot Index).=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWhat fact of engineering requires that it takes an entire human li=
fe to manufacture a private jet?=E2=80=9D he asked when we first spoke.=C2=
=A0
Spoiler: there isn=E2=80=99t one. It was just really complex, and hard for =
anyone to hold everything it would take to make one in their head.
Ian thought he could. By starting with very small things, like model airpla=
nes, and moving up to bigger things, like experimental airplanes, he had a =
sixth sense for how things fit together, and for what it takes to maintain =
them when they fall apart.=C2=A0
On First Principles, he told Christian, =E2=80=9CI just know that if you pu=
t this thing there, it=E2=80=99s going to be miserable to assemble and expe=
nsive to fix. Imagine you have a bunch of planes out there. How does the me=
chanic interact with it when it comes in for maintenance? You have to think=
 about the Mechanic Experience.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
If that seems like skipping a few steps ahead when Astro Mechanica hasn=E2=
=80=99t built a single aircraft yet, that=E2=80=99s the point as Ian sees i=
t.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CMost engineers don=E2=80=99t understand what=E2=80=99s involved in=
 actually making the thing they come up with,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=
=9CMy secret sauce is that I=E2=80=99ve spent my life becoming the person w=
ho builds the thing. I=E2=80=99m a pilot first and foremost, I know why thi=
ngs are engineered the way they are, and I know the manufacturing process. =
There=E2=80=99s always some trade-off, and it=E2=80=99s faster to make it i=
f one person is holding everything in their head.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
So that Wright Stuff=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
I wasn=E2=80=99t sure where to put this, but Ian has some strong Wright Bro=
thers vibes [ https://substack.com/redirect/a162090b-b40d-4a27-9b25-ee91c75=
50e84?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=
=C2=A0
The Wrights=E2=80=99 flight was made possible by advances in motors from th=
e automotive industry. The Wright Brothers started as bicycle repairmen, th=
en manufacturers, which gave them the capital, shop space, and intuition ne=
eded to build their plane.=C2=A0
When I told Ian about the connection I was trying to make, he laughed, befo=
re saying, =E2=80=9CI'd like to mention an amusing coincidence, I was born =
on Wilbur Wright's birthday, April 16th.=E2=80=9D
Get the fuck out of here. Come on.
I could make comparisons with Lockheed Skunkworks chief Kelly Johnson, who =
designed the P-38 Lightning, the SR-71 Blackbird, and the U-2, and who had =
such an aerodynamic intuition that his boss, Hall Hibbard, once exclaimed, =
=E2=80=9CThat damned Swede can actually see air.=E2=80=9D But I=E2=80=99ll =
save that.=C2=A0
The point isn=E2=80=99t to hype Ian up to an impossible altitude. His resul=
ts will speak for themselves, or they won=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
But given the ambition of his company: to usher in a new age of air travel,=
 win aerospace, and build a $1 trillion business, Ian will have to be as go=
od as the Wrights and Kelly Johnson eventually, and even better at building=
 a business. Few people make breakthroughs in flight. Few people build tril=
lion dollar businesses. The Venn Diagram overlap of the two is exactly 0.=
=C2=A0
But Ian wants to become the first. And to do that, he needed to start by ac=
tually building a team and a thing.=C2=A0
Enter Astro Mechanica
In late 2019 and early 2020, he started working on that idea for a regular =
subsonic private jet that could be at cost parity with airliners.=C2=A0
By 2021, thanks to time spent tinkering with that idea, he realized that a =
new type of electric adaptive engine would finally be possible thanks to ad=
vances in the performance of electric motors.=C2=A0
From idea to prototype took two months and $200k.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYou just need to prove the thing you=E2=80=99re trying to prove,=
=E2=80=9D Ian told Christian. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s the art of knowing what=
 does and doesn=E2=80=99t matter on this particular thing.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
By October 2022, he raised a round from LowerCarbon Capital. By March 2023,=
 funds in hand, Ian had hired his first aerospace engineers.=C2=A0
Astro Mechanica was moving out of Ian=E2=80=99s head and into a real compan=
y.
The Space Mongols=C2=A0
It might surprise you to learn that I am not an aerospace engineer, so to f=
igure out whether an aerospace engineer like Ian is legit, I need to look f=
or clues.=C2=A0
One clue might be a video of a working prototype, like the one we started t=
he piece with.=C2=A0
Another might be an endorsement from someone like Matt Parlmer.=C2=A0
Another, more important one is the ability to recruit badass engineers. On =
that count, Astro Mechanica is legit.=C2=A0
After raising from LowerCarbon, Ian spent the next six months looking for a=
 rare combination: an engineer who was experienced but not jaded. Too groun=
ded, and you end up with an unwillingness to try new things. Too head-in-th=
e-clouds, and you end up untethered from reality. And in engineering, reali=
ty always wins.=C2=A0
Finally, he found Matt Lehman: an OG SpaceX propulsion engineer who worked =
on Omelek Island setting up Falcon 1. Matt is a hardcore propulsion PhD wit=
h over two decades of experience building rockets at companies including No=
rthrop, Astra, and Ventions, but he=E2=80=99s also a surfer who lives in Sa=
nta Cruz and is down to try to catch the next wave.
With Matt onboard, the two got to work building out the Dream Team.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s Patrick McGuire, the Lead Engineer, Propulsion, who worked =
under Matt at Astra and Ventions. =E2=80=9CYou can throw anything at Patric=
k and he thinks about it appropriately,=E2=80=9D Ian said.=C2=A0
Then there=E2=80=99s Tyler Sandberg, who=E2=80=99s worked on propulsion at =
Blue Origin, SpaceX, and Astra.=C2=A0 =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s like a younger =
Patrick.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Most recently, Ian hired his mentor, someone he=E2=80=99s been trying to hi=
re for a long time: Jeff Tiedeken. =E2=80=9CElon poached Jeff for Neuralink=
, he was one of the first 20 people there and the first person building thi=
ngs. Larry Page hired him at (EVTOL company) KittyHawk [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/62d0015c-85ab-4647-bf8c-e3d10599fc46?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. He helped build nuclear reactor=
s at Kairos Power [ https://substack.com/redirect/345b3fb9-2db3-46ef-a487-0=
b432544c476?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] and led manufacturing at Astranis [ https://substack.com/redirect/734=
a4baa-e5b2-4c7c-83f2-37dc970c9258?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
=E2=80=9CHe doesn=E2=80=99t have a degree,=E2=80=9D Ian said, =E2=80=9Cbut =
everyone knows Jeff is the fucking man.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The team is now eight people, each of whom is an expert on one thing, but c=
an do most things.=C2=A0
Ian compared the way the team works to the Mongol Empire: =E2=80=9CEveryone=
 is self-sufficient and everyone can do all the things. Everyone is just ve=
ry capable.=E2=80=9D
Ian calls them the Space Mongols.=C2=A0
Ian thinks that they can get all the way to the flight engine with just nin=
e people =E2=80=93 fewer brains mean less opportunity for losses in communi=
cation, so it=E2=80=99s better to keep the team small and excellent, for no=
w. But at some point, they will need to scale.=C2=A0
Ian pictures the team growing fractally from strong cores.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CApple became more Apple over time as they hired excellent people,=
=E2=80=9D Ian said, =E2=80=9CI see the same thing starting to happen here.=
=E2=80=9D
There are three pillars of the business: Engines, Airframes, and Operations=
=2E=C2=A0
To date, they=E2=80=99ve built the core of the Engine team, because without=
 the engine, nothing else matters. This core =E2=80=93 the Space Mongols =
=E2=80=93 will make the next set of hires, which will make the next, and so=
 on out from there.=C2=A0
Next, Ian is replicating the Engine team=E2=80=99s structure to build out t=
he Airframes team, which will build the airplanes that the Engine team will=
 bolt its baby onto. This team should be about 12 people to get to a workin=
g airframe.=C2=A0
Then, they=E2=80=99ll replicate the org structure again to hire an Operatio=
ns team, which will work with regulators, partners, and customers to get th=
e engines and airframes into the sky.=C2=A0
Each one of these core teams will be the foundation for much bigger organiz=
ations along those same three lines as the company grows. If they get the f=
oundation just right, Ian thinks it should be able to scale up.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a clear parallel between the way Ian designs physical thing=
s and the way he designs teams: start with the small model, understand it i=
nside and out, understand how each piece trades off with the others, and on=
ly when you have a full intuition of the thing: scale it.=C2=A0
One of the bets on Astro Mechanica is that the same pattern holds for organ=
izations, or that Ian will be able to adapt if it doesn=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
But that=E2=80=99s a future problem, one that he=E2=80=99ll have to earn th=
e right to solve. First, they need to prove that this Turboelectric Adaptiv=
e Engine does what they think it can.=C2=A0
But First, the Engine
With the core team onboard, the past few months at Astro Mechanica have bee=
n busy. They raised a $3 million Seed from a16z=E2=80=99s American Dynamism=
 practice and joined the YC Winter 24 batch.=C2=A0
Most importantly, they=E2=80=99ve been building the actual flight engine, t=
he first of what the company hopes will be hundreds or thousands that will =
climb the atmosphere like a ladder and ride the specific impulse curve up t=
o Mach 2.7.=C2=A0
Astro Mechanica plans to unveil its engine live at YC Demo day next Wednesd=
ay in what has a shot to be one of the most memorable demos in the incubato=
r=E2=80=99s history.=C2=A0
Ian gave me a little sneak peek and told me I could show you if you promise=
 not to spoil the surprise:
The company has had as smooth a path as possible to this point in the journ=
ey, particularly for a company that=E2=80=99s building a new kind of jet en=
gine. I would imagine that VCs are going to be all over it after demo day (=
and that many are trying to get ahead of that rush as we speak).=C2=A0
VC funding isn=E2=80=99t a goal; it=E2=80=99s a destination. But in the cas=
e of this business, so much will depend on its ability to find financial pa=
rtners who support its more-for-more vision of aerospace that financing is =
as core to the business as the engine itself.=C2=A0
Cash is its fuel, and whether it crashes, simply sells a better engine, bui=
lds a nice launch business, or takes the baton from Boeing and drags aerosp=
ace into the Turboelectric Age will depend in large part on how it balances=
 its own speed and efficiency from here.=C2=A0
Pursuing Moonshots=C2=A0
Financialization couldn=E2=80=99t save Boeing, or the airline industry as w=
e know it.=20
Trying to get more-for-less without technological progress =E2=80=93 more r=
evenue on fewer assets by outsourcing, more seats in the same plane by shri=
nking seats =E2=80=93 is a one-way ticket to stagnation and decline.=C2=A0=
=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve argued that it=E2=80=99s not Boeing=E2=80=99s fault, or any of=
 the airlines=E2=80=99 fault, but a natural consequence of reaching the end=
 of a technological paradigm that=E2=80=99s had so much juice squeezed out =
of it already. It was inevitable.=C2=A0
Astro Mechanica wants to get more-for-less the right way: through technolog=
y. More speed for less cost through adaptive engines. That engine is just t=
he start.=C2=A0
Astro Mechanica plans to:=C2=A0
Build a new kind of engine: the Turboelectric Adaptive Engine=C2=A0
Use it to launch rockets
Use the cash and data from the rockets to build small private supersonic pl=
anes
Use the cash and data from the private planes to build commercial airliners
It wants its rockets to fly 1x per week and its private planes to fly 100x =
per week. To have a rebuild-the-airline-industry impact, its commercial pla=
nes will one day have to fly thousands of times per week.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s nothing inherently defensible about an engine design. The d=
efensibility in this business comes from getting to scale quickly, and from=
 building a unique business around the engine before anyone else does. Agai=
nst incumbents, it=E2=80=99s counter-positioned, which buys it time to scal=
e, and against potential new entrants, it has a head start, a strong team, =
and the whole master plan, down to the finest detail, in Andrew=E2=80=99s h=
ead.=C2=A0
In either case, it will need to get big as fast as it can. Turning out hund=
reds of aircraft orders of magnitude faster than they=E2=80=99re assembled =
today will require manufacturing prowess on par with a Tesla Gigafactory, a=
nd like Tesla, it will require boatloads of cash.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s OK. That=E2=80=99s good. We should give our most ambitious p=
rojects the most money. We should give them more so that they can give us b=
ack more, for less.=C2=A0
Astro Mechanica is a Techno-Industrial [ https://substack.com/redirect/1b3e=
b3bc-9d95-433e-94d7-1366fde5a048?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. It=E2=80=99s using new technology to build bett=
er atoms-based products at a lower cost than was previously possible.=C2=A0
Instead of simply selling cheaper products into the existing web of mediocr=
ity that is the airline industry, Astro Mechanica wants to rebuild the whol=
e thing. Of course that=E2=80=99s going to take cash.=C2=A0
I think we=E2=80=99re all scarred from the more-for-less era into believing=
 that costs don=E2=80=99t shrink, that legacy industries don=E2=80=99t get =
rebuilt, that change only comes at the margins.=C2=A0
But what fact of engineering requires that the way it=E2=80=99s been done i=
s the only way it can be done?=C2=A0
Boeing won the Jet Age by harnessing a new technology to reshape an industr=
y, and it improved the way billions of passengers travel in the process. Th=
at it=E2=80=99s stagnating now doesn=E2=80=99t mean that air travel is doom=
ed to decay, but that it=E2=80=99s time for a new Age.=C2=A0
Boeing dominated through the period that Tyler Cowen calls The Great Stagna=
tion [ https://substack.com/redirect/bafa59d3-b109-406b-920b-296a359f15c3?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a half=
-century on a technological plateau defined by many of the evils that ate a=
t airlines.=C2=A0
The Great Stagnation is ending. You can feel it.=C2=A0
SpaceX launches multiple rockets a week. Solar is getting very cheap. EVs a=
re overtaking gas-powered cars. Ozempic is helping millions lose weight.=C2=
=A0
Maybe Astro Mechanica will bring affordable supersonic travel to humankind.=
=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s going to take a ton of work, time, capital, luck, skill, and a=
daptability. It will take getting the core of each piece of the business ri=
ght, and then growing fractally out from there while maintaining fidelity w=
ith the original thing. It will take becoming great at things that the comp=
any has never done.=C2=A0
If it really has a more-for-less engine, there are a million ways for Astro=
 Mechanica to make high-margin revenue in the short-term that require a lot=
 less work, time, capital, luck, skill, and adaptability than this crazy pl=
an to build The Aerospace Company over decades.=C2=A0
But if Astro Mechanica really has a more-for-less engine, it must pursue th=
e moonshot. I want to live in a world that supports that pursuit.
Thanks to Ian for letting me tell the Astro Mechanica story, to Christian f=
or input and feedback, and to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/55572882-=
914a-484f-a190-73e4a5dc2c15?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for editing!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox tomorrow =
with a Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

