s blame leadership, mergers, financialization, MBAs, lack of competition, A=
merica&#8217;s general decline, even wokeness. What they all miss is that <=
/span><strong>this was inevitable</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Boeing is an interchangeable actor in an ongoing story about the =
death and rebirth of technological paradigms. From Ford and GM to Tesla; fr=
om IBM to Apple and Microsoft.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The airline=
 industry is now in the 66th year of the </span><strong>Jet Age</strong><sp=
an>, the era that Boeing defined and dominated from the start.&#160;</span>=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">There&#8217;s simply no room left for real improvemen=
t &#8211; today&#8217;s turbofan engines carry planes as fast and efficient=
ly as they physically can, airlines squeeze as many passengers into the sam=
e sized airframes as possible, airports squeeze as many planes into their g=
ates as they can each day.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Financializatio=
n can slice up a fixed pie. Only technological progress can </span><em>grow=
</em><span> the pie.&#160;</span></p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget=
" style=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: an=
