6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">For Boeing, which introduced t=
he Jet Age, to continue to progress, it would need to completely shift the =
paradigm in which it operates.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It would need to =
bet on a new type of engine, and then adapt the complex web of relationship=
s and interdependencies to that core decision: new airframe designs, new su=
pply chains, new manufacturing processes, new everything. It would need to =
relinquish its comfortable duopoly position and convince its customers to b=
uy something new and unproven.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s both diffi=
cult and risky. So instead, it tries to squeeze every last drop out of the =
existing paradigm by tweaking designs here and there, outsourcing everythin=
g it can, and focusing on efficiency. It stands still and holds on for dear=
 life.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But the problem, as Christian reminded me=
, is that the quality assurance problems Boeing is experiencing are exactly=
 what happens when you stand still. If you&#8217;re not progressing, entrop=
y kills you.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s true for the airframes=
 themselves, and it&#8217;s true for the experience of flying. Because as a=
irlines compete to serve more customers with basically a fixed set of resou=
rces, experience suffers.&#160;</p><h4 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" =
